context: <a0_0><b14_0>Saint Athanasius of <b18_0>Alexandria<b18_0/><b14_0/><a0_0/> (/ˌæθəˈneɪʃəs/; Greek: Ἀθανάσιος Ἀλεξανδρείας, Athanásios Alexandrías; c. 296–298 – <a4_0>2 May <b13_0>373<b13_0/><a4_0/>), also called <a1_0><a5_0><b15_0>Athanasius the Great<b15_0/><a5_0/><a1_0/>, <a8_0>Athanasius the Confessor<a8_0/> or, primarily in the Coptic Orthodox Church, Athanasius the Apostolic, was the twentieth bishop of <a6_0><b11_0>Alexandria<b11_0/><a6_0/> (as Athanasius I). His episcopate lasted <a2_0><a7_0><b9_0><b16_0>45 years<b16_0/><b9_0/><a7_0/><a2_0/> (<b10_0>c. 8 June 328 – 2 May 373<b10_0/>), of which over <a3_0><b17_0>17<b17_0/><a3_0/> were spent in <b12_0>five<b12_0/> exiles ordered by four different Roman emperors.
